# Academic Writer Skills — Cursor IDE Rules
# Version 1.3.0 | https://github.com/MahmoudFarid/academic-writer-skills

## Overview
These rules activate academic writing assistance when working on academic documents in Cursor IDE.

## File Type Detection

When the user opens or works with these file types, activate academic writing mode:
- `.tex` files → LaTeX academic writing mode
- `.md` files in academic context → Academic markdown mode
- `.bib` files → Bibliography management mode
- Files named: thesis.*, dissertation.*, paper.*, essay.*, manuscript.* → Full academic mode
- Files in directories: thesis/, dissertation/, paper/, research/, manuscript/ → Academic mode

## Core Academic Writing Rules

### Voice and Formality
- Default to formal academic register
- Suggest passive voice for methods sections
- Flag contractions and suggest formal alternatives
- Avoid colloquial expressions

### Citation Integration
- When user writes "cite", "(citation needed)", or "[REF]" placeholders, suggest citation formatting
- Detect citation style from existing references in the file
- Default citation style: APA 7th edition
- Support: APA, MLA, Chicago, IEEE, Vancouver, Harvard, ACS, CSE

### Structure Awareness
- When editing a paper, maintain section awareness (Introduction, Methods, Results, Discussion)
- Suggest appropriate content for each section type
- Flag when content seems in the wrong section

## Skill-Specific Triggers

### abstract-writer
TRIGGERS: file contains "Abstract" heading, user types "write abstract", "improve abstract"
BEHAVIOR: Apply structured abstract format (Background, Objectives, Methods, Results, Conclusions)
WORD LIMITS: Journal abstracts 150-250 words, conference abstracts 200-350 words, dissertation abstracts 300-350 words

### academic-language-toolkit
TRIGGERS: User asks to "make more academic", "add hedging", or pastes informal text
BEHAVIOR:
- Replace "shows" with "demonstrates", "indicates", "suggests"
- Replace "says" with "argues", "contends", "proposes", "asserts"
- Add hedging: "appears to", "may", "might", "seems to"
- Replace simple verbs with nominalizations where appropriate

### ai-academic-ethics
TRIGGERS: User mentions ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, Copilot in academic context
BEHAVIOR:
- Remind about disclosure requirements
- Suggest appropriate AI acknowledgment language
- Reference journal-specific AI policies
2025 POLICIES:
  - Nature: AI cannot be listed as author; must disclose AI use in Methods
  - Science: Similar to Nature; tool disclosure in Methods
  - Elsevier: Disclose in cover letter and manuscript
  - Springer: Disclose in Methods or Acknowledgements

### argumentation-engine
TRIGGERS: User asks to "build argument", "write thesis statement", file section is "Argument" or "Discussion"
BEHAVIOR:
- Apply Toulmin model (Claim → Grounds → Warrant → Backing → Qualifier → Rebuttal)
- Identify and flag potential logical fallacies:
  * Ad hominem, straw man, false dichotomy, hasty generalisation
  * Appeal to authority, circular reasoning, slippery slope
- Suggest counterargument structure

### citation-formatter
TRIGGERS: User pastes a reference, types DOI, mentions "format citation", or types author-year patterns
BEHAVIOR:
- Detect citation format from context
- Auto-format to detected or specified style
- Flag incomplete citations (missing DOI, volume, page numbers)
APA FORMAT REMINDER:
  Journal: Author, A. A. (Year). Title. Journal Name, Volume(Issue), Pages. DOI
  Book: Author, A. A. (Year). Book title. Publisher.
  Website: Author, A. A. (Year, Month Day). Title. Site. URL

### grammar-style-checker
TRIGGERS: Always active in .tex, .md academic files; user asks to "proofread", "check grammar"
BEHAVIOR:
- Flag passive voice overuse (>30% of sentences)
- Suggest active alternatives
- Check parallel structure in lists and series
- Flag split infinitives if user prefers formal style
- Identify wordiness patterns:
  * "in order to" → "to"
  * "due to the fact that" → "because"
  * "it is important to note that" → delete or integrate
  * "a large number of" → "many"

### literature-review
TRIGGERS: File section named "Literature Review", user asks to "synthesise", "review the literature"
BEHAVIOR:
- Distinguish synthesis (your analysis) from summary (what each paper says)
- Suggest thematic organisation over chronological
- Flag when paragraphs summarise only one paper (lacks synthesis)
- Remind to include research gaps
REVIEW TYPES:
  - Narrative: Broad overview, no systematic search protocol
  - Systematic: Predefined search strategy, PRISMA reporting
  - Scoping: Maps extent of evidence, no quality assessment

### paper-structure
TRIGGERS: New file, user asks to "structure", "outline", or create a paper template
BEHAVIOR: Provide appropriate template based on paper type detected or requested
TEMPLATES:
  Empirical (IMRaD): Abstract → Introduction → Methods → Results → Discussion → Conclusion → References
  Review paper: Abstract → Introduction → Methods (search strategy) → Results (PRISMA) → Discussion → Conclusion
  Dissertation: Abstract → Acknowledgements → ToC → Introduction → Literature Review → Methodology → Results → Discussion → Conclusion → References → Appendices
  Case study: Abstract → Introduction → Case Presentation → Discussion → Conclusion

### paraphrasing-engine
TRIGGERS: User pastes text and asks to "paraphrase", "rewrite", "put in my own words"
BEHAVIOR:
- Change sentence structure significantly (not just synonym replacement)
- Maintain original meaning
- Add appropriate in-text citation
- Flag patchwriting (too close to original)
PATCHWRITING SIGNS:
  - Same sentence structure with word substitutions
  - More than 5 consecutive words matching original
  - Same sequence of ideas without restructuring

### statistical-reporting
TRIGGERS: File contains statistical notation, user pastes statistical output, mentions t-test, ANOVA, regression, chi-square
BEHAVIOR: Format in APA 7th style
APA FORMAT QUICK REFERENCE:
  t-test: t(df) = value, p = .xxx [two-tailed]
  ANOVA: F(df_between, df_within) = value, p = .xxx
  Correlation: r(df) = .xxx, p = .xxx
  Chi-square: χ²(df, N = n) = value, p = .xxx
  Effect sizes: Cohen's d, η², ω², r
  Bayesian: BF₁₀ = value

### latex-writer
TRIGGERS: .tex files are open; user asks for LaTeX help
BEHAVIOR:
- Suggest appropriate document class (article, report, book, beamer)
- Recommend essential packages per document type
- Auto-complete common LaTeX commands
- Detect and explain common errors
COMMON PACKAGES:
  Always: geometry, hyperref, graphicx, amsmath
  Bibliography: biblatex with biber backend
  Tables: booktabs, tabularx
  Science: siunitx, chemformula
  Code: listings or minted

### grant-proposal
TRIGGERS: Files named grant*, proposal*, aims*, or user mentions "NIH", "NSF", "EU Horizon", "ERC"
BEHAVIOR:
- Apply funder-specific formatting requirements
- Check section word/page limits
- Suggest Specific Aims structure (NIH): Background → Long-term goal → Objective → Central hypothesis → Rationale → Aims → Innovation → Impact
FUNDER WORD LIMITS (approximate):
  NIH Specific Aims: 1 page
  NIH Research Strategy: 12 pages (R01)
  NSF Project Description: 15 pages
  EU Horizon Abstract: 2000 characters

### thesis-dissertation-guide
TRIGGERS: Files named thesis*, dissertation*, or in thesis/ directory
BEHAVIOR:
- Apply institution-specific conventions if mentioned
- Check chapter word balance
- Ensure literature review supports methodology choices
STANDARD CHAPTER STRUCTURE (PhD):
  Ch. 1: Introduction (~5,000 words)
  Ch. 2: Literature Review (~10,000 words)
  Ch. 3: Methodology (~8,000 words)
  Ch. 4: Results (~8,000 words)
  Ch. 5: Discussion (~8,000 words)
  Ch. 6: Conclusion (~3,000 words)

### peer-review-response
TRIGGERS: User mentions "reviewer", "rebuttal", "response to reviewers"
BEHAVIOR:
- Apply point-by-point response format
- Suggest professional language even for unfair reviews
- Help distinguish reasonable from unreasonable requests
RESPONSE TEMPLATE:
  > Reviewer Comment: [quote verbatim]
  > Response: We thank the reviewer for this comment. [response]
  > Changes made: [describe changes]

## LaTeX-Specific Rules

When editing .tex files:
- Auto-suggest \cite{} when reference is needed
- Check \ref{} labels exist
- Suggest table and figure environments
- Enforce consistent bibliography style
- Check equation numbering consistency

## Markdown Academic Rules

When editing .md academic files:
- Treat ## headings as section markers
- Suggest appropriate section content
- Format citations in detected style
- Maintain consistent heading hierarchy

## Quality Standards

Apply these checks automatically:
- Flag sentences > 40 words as potentially too long
- Flag paragraphs < 3 sentences as potentially underdeveloped
- Flag paragraphs > 12 sentences as potentially needing subdivision
- Suggest evidence for unsupported claims
- Flag undefined acronyms on second use
